    <h2 id="why-vitamin-a">Why Vitamin A Remains One of the Most Important Micronutrients for Human Health</h2>

    <p>Vitamin A is a fat-soluble nutrient that the World Health Organization calls "the most important micronutrient for the immune system." It performs essential functions in vision — producing rhodopsin, the light-sensitive pigment in your retinal photoreceptors that enables you to see in low-light conditions. It maintains the integrity of mucosal surfaces in the respiratory tract, gut, and urinary system — your body's first line of defense against pathogens. It regulates cellular differentiation, ensuring that stem cells develop into the specialized cells your tissues need. And it supports skin health at the cellular level, from keratinocyte maturation to collagen synthesis.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">250M</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">preschool-age children worldwide are affected by vitamin A deficiency, according to the WHO. It remains the leading cause of preventable childhood blindness globally and increases mortality risk from measles and diarrheal diseases by 20-24% in deficient populations.</p>
    </div>

    <p>In the United States, clinical vitamin A deficiency is uncommon, but subclinical insufficiency is more prevalent than most people realize. A 2016 analysis using NHANES data found that approximately 45% of American adults do not meet the Estimated Average Requirement for vitamin A from food alone. Groups at higher risk include those with fat malabsorption conditions (celiac disease, Crohn's disease, cystic fibrosis), individuals with chronic alcohol use, strict vegans, and the elderly. For these populations, a well-formulated vitamin A gummy provides an accessible, safe way to close the nutritional gap.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
