      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Reproduction and growth</strong>
        <p>Vitamin A is essential for spermatogenesis, fetal development, and bone growth. It regulates gene expression involved in embryonic development, particularly of the heart, lungs, and skeletal system.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2019 Cochrane review analyzing <strong>47 randomized controlled trials</strong> with over 1.2 million children found that vitamin A supplementation in deficient populations <strong>reduced all-cause mortality by 12%, diarrhea-related mortality by 12%, and measles-related mortality by 50%</strong>. These findings form the basis of the WHO's global vitamin A supplementation program.</p>
      <cite>Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews, 2019 — 47 RCTs, 1.2 million children</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Beta-Carotene vs. Retinol: Why the Form of Vitamin A in Your Gummy Matters</h3>

    <p>The most critical decision in choosing a vitamin A gummy is the form of vitamin A it contains. Retinol (preformed vitamin A) is the active form — your body uses it directly. But retinol is fat-soluble and accumulates in the liver. Chronic intake exceeding the Tolerable Upper Intake Level of 3,000mcg RAE (10,000 IU) can cause hypervitaminosis A, with symptoms ranging from headaches and nausea to liver damage and, during pregnancy, birth defects. Beta-carotene, by contrast, is a provitamin A carotenoid that your body converts to retinol only as needed. This self-regulating conversion makes beta-carotene virtually impossible to overdose. Our top picks prioritize beta-carotene or mixed-source formulas that stay well within safe limits.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Label reading tip:</strong> Look for the vitamin A source on the supplement facts panel. "Beta-carotene" or "mixed carotenoids" are the safest forms for daily supplementation. "Retinyl palmitate" or "retinyl acetate" indicate preformed vitamin A — effective but with a lower safety margin. Dose is measured in mcg RAE (Retinol Activity Equivalents) or IU (1 mcg RAE = 3.33 IU from retinol, or 1 mcg RAE = 20 IU from beta-carotene).</p>
    </div>

