    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Vitamin A: What the Science Says</h4>
      <p>Vitamin A is one of the most extensively researched micronutrients, with clinical evidence spanning vision, immunity, skin health, and reproduction.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Vitamin A and Vision</strong>
          <p>Vitamin A produces rhodopsin, the photoreceptor pigment essential for night vision. Deficiency causes night blindness, progressing to xerophthalmia and potentially permanent blindness.<br /><em>WHO Global Report on Vision, 2019</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Immune Function</strong>
          <p>Vitamin A supplementation in deficient populations reduced all-cause child mortality by 12% and measles-related mortality by 50% across 47 RCTs.<br /><em>Cochrane Review, 2019</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Beta-Carotene Safety</strong>
          <p>Unlike preformed retinol, beta-carotene is self-regulating — the body converts only what it needs. This eliminates the risk of hypervitaminosis A from beta-carotene sources.<br /><em>NIH Office of Dietary Supplements</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Skin Health</strong>
          <p>Retinoids (vitamin A derivatives) are the most evidence-based topical anti-aging compounds in dermatology. Oral vitamin A supports keratinocyte differentiation and collagen synthesis systemically.<br /><em>J Drugs in Dermatology, 2017</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

