    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin A Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does vitamin A do in the body?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin A is essential for vision (producing rhodopsin for night vision), immune function (maintaining mucosal barriers and T-cell production), skin health (regulating keratinocyte differentiation), and cellular growth. The WHO calls it the most important micronutrient for immune function.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between retinol and beta-carotene?</summary>
      <p>Retinol is preformed vitamin A used directly by the body but can cause toxicity at high doses. Beta-carotene is a provitamin A that converts to retinol only as needed, making it virtually impossible to overdose. The conversion ratio is approximately 12:1.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin A should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 900mcg RAE for men and 700mcg RAE for women. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 3,000mcg RAE from preformed retinol. This upper limit does not apply to beta-carotene, which is self-regulating.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can you take too much vitamin A?</summary>
      <p>Yes — preformed retinol can accumulate in the liver and cause toxicity at sustained doses exceeding 3,000mcg RAE per day. Beta-carotene does not cause toxicity — the worst effect of excess beta-carotene is harmless skin yellowing (carotenodermia).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should pregnant women take vitamin A gummies?</summary>
      <p>Pregnant women should be cautious with preformed vitamin A (retinol), as doses exceeding 3,000mcg RAE have been associated with birth defects. Beta-carotene is generally considered safe during pregnancy. Always consult your OB/GYN before supplementing.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the signs of vitamin A deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Night blindness is the earliest sign. Progressive deficiency can cause dry eyes, Bitot spots, corneal damage, dry skin, increased infections, and impaired wound healing. Clinical deficiency is rare in the US but subclinical insufficiency affects many adults.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is vitamin A good for skin health?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Vitamin A regulates keratinocyte differentiation, collagen synthesis, and acts as an antioxidant. Retinoids are the most evidence-based anti-aging ingredients in dermatology. Oral supplementation supports these pathways systemically over weeks to months.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I get enough vitamin A from food alone?</summary>
      <p>Most people eating a varied diet can meet vitamin A needs through food. Top sources include beef liver, sweet potatoes, carrots, spinach, and dairy. People with fat malabsorption disorders, strict vegans, and the elderly may benefit from supplementation.</p>
    </details>

    <!-- WARN BOX -->
